The definite article and the deictic particle se constitute a discontinuous marker used as an attributive demonstrative. The phrase consists of article + noun + particle, e.g. an map se 'that son', e-n ty se 'in that house'. from je 'that' (pronoun, not determiner) and -ci. The origin of -ci is the same as in Iron. The pronominal root je is from PIr. *ay-, cf. Av. ayÉ™m. This root does not exist in Iron at all, but is clearly a Digor archaism. Proto-Ossetic apparently had three degrees of deixis; Digor still has them in the determiners (a-ci, je-ci, wo-ci), but merged je and wo into a single paradigm in the pronoun. In Iron *je disappeared entirely.
In the Canon it is attested in prepositional phrases with the meaning 'on the left' only. However, in younger texts it is attested as a adjective 'left' too.

The definite article and the deictic particle se constitute a discontinuous marker used as an attributive demonstrative. The phrase consists of article + noun + particle, e.g. an den man 'this man', an fest man 'this festival'. Note that Middle Breton has a threefold deictic system: an ... man 'here (near me) / this', an ... se 'there (near you) / that', an ... hont 'yonder'.

Present indivative 3 sg., cf. also dibu preterite 3 sg. 'he/she came'. The paradigm of the verb TO COME is highly suppletive in Brittonic. The forms of the present indicative are based on PIE *hâ‚‚agÌ‘- in Middle and Modern Welsh, and also in Middle Cornish and Breton. In addition to this, Old and Middle Welsh possess compounds consisting of *tu- + bot 'to be' (PIE *bÊ°uÌ¯ehâ‚‚-). The original meaning of these forms probably was 'to be present' (Schumacher 2004, 192, note d), Schumacher 2011, 186). Evans (1964, 133) lists MW dybyd etc. as "consuetudinal present and future", MW dybu as "preterite 2". This additional notion could be present in the OW forms as well. In view of Middle Welsh, the existence of forms based on Proto-Celtic *ag- seems probable. These forms most likely conveyed the basic meaning of COMING, without any additional notions. They are not attested in Old Welsh, however, due to the fragmentary nature of the corpus.

This may strike speakers of many varieties of English as unusual, but needs to be seen in the context of significant differences between different varieties of English worldwide.  Highly relevant is that in the variety of English targeted here, i.e. standard British English and following majority usage in England, the lexemes 'ill' and 'unwell' are very widely used, where other varieties use 'sick'.  This allows a particular usage of '(being) sick', in the specific sense of vomiting, especially in the most common aspectual and tense uses.  So in this specific variety, in the default, unmarked register, speakers most often use formulations like "S/he has been sick" to mean not "S/he has been ill" (as they would normally refer to a period of ill health), but to mean specifically "S/he has (just) vomited":  Likewise, normal usage would be: "Please stop the car, Iâ€™m going to be sick.", meaning specifically that the speaker felt s/he was about to vomit.

The lexeme 'vomit' in this variety has rather narrower register uses, slightly elevated ad 'medical'.  There are also a host of other familiar register lexemes, as in other varieties of English.

Although also the name of the internal organ 'stomach', in the variety of English targeted here, i.e. standard British English and following majority usage in England, the word 'stomach' has broadened to refer to the abdomen in general, and is has become the default, unmarked word for the target sense here.  The lexeme 'belly' is more marked in register, often with overtones of a protruding 'pot belly'..
